             = <!-- {{URL|school.url}} or {{URL|1=school.url}} if the url contains an equals sign -->\n| picture_caption2       =\n| lastupdate             = \n}}\n\n'''Central Hindu Boys School''' aka '''C.H.S''' is a [[Single-sex education|boys]] [[Secondary school#India|secondary school]] (day school with [[hostel]] facility) in Kamachha, [[Bhelupur, Varanasi|Bhelupur]], [[Varanasi]]. It was established in 1898 by [[Annie Besant]]. Since, it is the nucleus of [[Banaras Hindu University]], it is one of the prestigious schools  in India.<ref name=\"About\">{{cite news|title=About|publisher=Official website|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/chs/index.html}}</ref><ref name=\"School Info\">{{cite news|title=School Info|publisher=Varanasi.org|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.varanasi.org.in/central-hindu-school}}</ref><ref name=\"Location\">{{cite news|title=Location|publisher=Latlong.net|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.latlong.net/}}</ref><ref name=\"School details\">{{cite news|title=School details|publisher=[[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]] website|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.icbse.com/schools/central-hindu-boys-sr-sec-school/2130037}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Annie Besant, LoC.jpg|thumb|right|165px|[[Annie Besant]] in 1897]]\n[[File:Madan Mohan Malaviya 01.JPG|thumb|right|165px|Statue of [[Pandit Madan Mohan Malaviya]] in compound of [[Shri Vishwanath Mandir]]]]\n\n==History==\nAsia's first Educational conference was held in the ground of the Central Hindu Boys School.\nCentral Hindu Boys School was established in 1898 by [[Dr. (title)|Dr.]] [[Annie Besant]]. Ruler of the [[India]]n [[Princely State]] of [[Benares State]] ([[Royal House of Benares]]) [[Prabhu Narayan Singh]] was instrumental in setting up the school and donated requisite land for the school.\n\nIt started as [[High school#India|high school]] (from grade [[Sixth grade|VI]] to [[X]]). [[Annie Besant]] originally intended to convert this school into a [[Undergraduate education#Indian system|degree college]] and sought approval from Prayag Vishwavidyalaya ([[Allahabad University]]). The school also housed classes for [[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University]] and ran classes as loner for the [[Banaras Hindu University]].\n\nIn 1914, on request of [[Pandit Madan Mohan Malaviya]], Besant handed over the college (then known as Central Hindu College) to [[Banaras Hindu University]] for establishing the university.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=uBSEJznCfJkC&pg=RA1-PA479&dq=%22Central+Hindu+College%22#PRA1-PA479,M1 History of Central Hindu College] ''Dr. Rajendra Prasad, Correspondence and Select Documents'', by [[Rajendra Prasad]], Valmiki Choudhary. [[Allied Publishers]], 1984. {{ISBN|81-7023-002-0}}. Page 479.</ref>\n\n===Association with [[Banaras Hindu University|BHU]]===\nThe school housed the first [[Faculty (division)|faculty]] ([[Faculty of Arts, Banaras Hindu University|Faculty of Arts]]) of [[Banaras Hindu University]] till 1916. [[Banaras Hindu University]] was started on the campus of this school (with class rooms on loan) and functioned there till it relocated to its current location in 1916. In 1914 [[Pandit Madan Mohan Malaviya]] requested [[Dr. (title)|Dr.]] [[Annie Besant|Besant]] to hand over the school (then called Central Hindu College) to [[Banaras Hindu University]]. On 27 November 1915, the school was handed over to the university. The school became a constituent college of the [[Banaras Hindu University]] in October 1917 after the Government issued a notification. The [[Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library, BHU]] was first housed in the Telang Library of the College in 1917.<ref name=\"Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library\">{{cite news|title=Sayaji Rao Gaekwad Library|publisher=coral.uchicago.edu|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=https://coral.uchicago.edu:8443/display/lasa/Banaras+Hindu+University,+Central+Library+%28Varanasi,+India%29}}</ref> Noted theosophist, [[George Arundale]] joined the school as a history teacher in 1917 and later became the head of the school.\n\nTill 1976, [[Banaras Hindu University]] had been conducting [[High school#India|High School]] (grade [[Tenth grade|X]]) of the school. Senior High School (11th standard) was called Pre University Course (PUC) and later the same students could join [[Banaras Hindu University]] directly for their undergraduate courses. In 1976, the school adopted the [[10+2]] education system and got affiliated with [[Central Board of Secondary Education|CBSE]]. The school is a part of the [[Banaras Hindu University]] and is governed by its administration.<ref name=\"About\"/><ref name=\"History\">{{cite news|title=History|publisher=Official website|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/chs/history.html}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nCentral Hindu Boys School's campus spreads over 70 acres and houses the school, [[hostel]], [[laboratories]] ([[Physics]], [[Chemistry]], [[Biology]], [[Mathematics]], [[Computer]], [[Psychology]] & [[Agriculture]]), [[gym]] and [[library]]. The school library has more than 30,000 publications. The school has over 50 classrooms and houses several halls.\n\n[[Football pitch|Football field]], [[cricket field]], [[basketball court]] and [[tennis court]]s are amongst the sporting facilities available. Annual inter school football competition, which is held at the school grounds, is one of the major sport event of the school.<ref name=\"Facilities\">{{cite news|title=Facilities|publisher=Official website|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/chs/librajhi ry.html}}</ref>\n\n==Academic programs ==\n\nThe school offers education from grade [[Sixth grade|VI]] to [[Twelfth grade|XII]] in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]] mediums. From grades [[Sixth grade|VI]] to [[Tenth grade|X]], all students follow same [[curriculum]] with exception of 'optional' subjects and medium of education; in grades [[Eleventh grade|XI]] and [[Twelfth grade|XII]], students can opt between [[Science]], [[Commerce]] and [[Liberal arts education|arts]] as main [[Course (education)|courses]].<ref name=\"Courses\">{{cite news|title=Courses|publisher=Official website|accessdate=19 Jul 2015|url=http://www.bhu.ac.in/chs/academic.html}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book| title =Sanatana Dharma: An advanced text book of Hindu religion and Ethics|publisher=Central Hindu College, Benaras|year=1904| url = https://archive.org/stream/sanatanadharmaad00benaiala#page/n3/mode/2up  }}\n\n==Noted alumni==\n* Dr. Subodh Kumar Singh: a plastic surgeon whose work was documented in ''[[Smile Pinki]]'', an award-winning documentary\n*[[Jayant Narlikar]]: Indian [[astrophysicist]].\n*[[K. N. Govindacharya]]: [[Social]] and [[political]]  [[activism|activist]]\n*[[Kamalapati Tripathi]]: Writer, journalist, editor, [[List of Indian independence activists|freedom-fighter]], Politician, [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh ]] and [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Union Minister for Railways]].\n*[[Kaushalendra Singh]]: Mayor of Varanasi\n* [[Ajay Kumar Yadav]]: I.A.S [[Himachal Pradesh]].\n*[[Omprakash Singh]]: Politician\n*[[Sri Prakasa]]: Politician, [[List of Indian independence activists|freedom-fighter]], [[Governor]] & administrator. India's first [[High Commissioner]] to [[Pakistan]].\n\n==Former principal==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! # !! Name !! Post !! Year of joining\n|-\n| 1 || Dr. Arthur Richardson ||  Principal || 1898\n|-\n| 2 || Benbari || Principal || 1899\n|-\n| 3 || J. S. Arundale || Principal ||  1904\n|-\n| 4 || Ikbalnarayangurtu || Principal  || 1910\n|-\n| 5 || I. J. S Taraporewala ||  Principal || 1913\n|-\n| 6 || Ratilal Desai || Acting Principal || 1918\n|-\n| 7 || Pandit Guru Sevak Upadhayay ||  Principal || 1919\n|-\n| 8 || Pandit N. K. Sukhiya ||  Principal || 1921\n|-\n| 9 || Pandit R. N. Mishra || Principal  || 1923\n|-\n| 10 || Pandit Ganga Datt Pandey ||  Principal || 1938\n|-\n| 11 || Pandit Narsingh Lal || Acting Principal || 1940\n|-\n| 12 || Pandit K. P. 